Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.41,0:25:18.04,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs40\bord2\fade(0,600)\an4\pos(760,520)}Paul Geromini \N Perevodildo\N Ziusudra\N History Asian \N Moozzi2
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.12,0:01:44.67,Default,,0,0,0,,On December 8th, 1941,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.67,0:01:50.33,Default,,0,0,0,,the IJN initiated the war on the Pacific \Nby launching a surprise attack on the American pacific fleet,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.33,0:01:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,stationed in Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. {lit: removed the apron of a gun; cover for the touch-hole on a cannon or matchlock​}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.40,0:01:59.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, commanded by \NLieutenant-General Yamashita, the Japanese Army
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.38,0:02:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,was poised to seize \Nthe crucial British redoubt of far east - Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.08,0:02:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,To that effect, they landed \Non the northern coast of Malay Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.08,0:02:10.17,Default,,0,0,0,,They were given the strategic goal
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.17,0:02:16.17,Default,,0,0,0,,of traversing the Malay Peninsula and capturing the great British fortress of Singapore in just under 90 days.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.72,0:02:19.43,Default,,0,0,0,,For that, blitzkrieg tactics had been adopted.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.81,0:02:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Later on, in February 1st, 1942,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.02,0:02:38.75,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese troops were already on the doorstep \Nof Singapore, in the coastal town of Johor Bahru.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.29,0:02:56.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Ships of capital interest for the British Far Eastern Fleet - \NPrince of Wales and Repulse, had also been sunk.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.38,0:03:00.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese had become the undisputed masters \Nof the skies and seas.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.01,0:03:06.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Singapore being completely shut down, \Nits capitulation was believed to be but a matter of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.79,0:03:09.56,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(0,300)} \h            Repulse \NKuantan                    \h \N\h                         Prince of Wales
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.56,0:03:12.59,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(300,500)}Johor Bahru \NBukit Timah Heights {/high ground; plateau; heights} \NSingapore
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.13,0:03:19.22,Sign,,0,0,200,,{\fade(300,00)\c&HCED9D4&\bord0\blur1\b1\xshad7\4c&H9A5E63&\4a&H93&} Episode 5 \N {\fs100} The Fall of Singapore {シンガポール攻略}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.24,0:03:26.58,Default,,0,0,0,,However, upon immediate danger \NSingapore was exposed to,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.58,0:03:30.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The British Far Eastern commander, \NLieutenant-General Percival said:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.91,0:03:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,"It if of utmost importance for a commander \Nto keep the lid on premature Intel. {lit: ... must be most of all cautious not to circulate (a rumour, information, etc.); to spread; to distribute the hasty/quick information"}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.38,0:03:40.26,Default,,0,0,0,,As by not doing so, the risk is undermining \Nthe morale of the troops."
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.76,0:03:45.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But I'm convinced that moping around\Nis way more detrimental to my men's motivation.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.01,0:03:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Our army is tasked with holding Singapore \Nto the last man, for three months at least.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.18,0:03:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, then, not redeploy{/retreat} \Nthe forces on Malay Peninsula to Singapore Island,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.66,0:03:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,so as to mount an organized defense? {/repulse the japanese}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.69,0:03:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,No! On it, there are not nearly enough barracks \Nto host everybody.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.05,0:04:00.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant-General Percival flatly dismissed
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.61,0:04:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,all the suggestions of the 8th Australian \NDivision Commander with a single word.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.04,0:04:17.25,Default,,0,0,0,,For the Malay Peninsula it is over. \NBut the struggle for Singapore is still afoot!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.25,0:04:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Presently, our British army \Nis all but trapped in this Fortress of Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.84,0:04:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Our common duty is to hold out \Nin this fortress until reinforcements arrive. {to hold out (e.g. against an attack); to hang on; to withstand; to endure; to last}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.79,0:04:36.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the commander of the British Far Eastern Army
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.23,0:04:41.05,Default,,0,0,0,,never precisely specified \Nhow the defense of Singapore had to be carried out.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.86,0:04:47.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Neither the citizens nor the soldiers \Nfelt much change in their everyday lives.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.79,0:05:01.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, it became quiet in Johor province, \Nacross the strait separating it from Singapore. {lit: on the other side of singapore - I hope he means this}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.13,0:05:07.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army seemingly \Nstopped carrying out any operations at all. {/movements/maneuvers/actions}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.01,0:06:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,But during that tranquil period, the Japanese army earnestly put the finishing touches to their attack on Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.15,0:06:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,But still, the whole process \Nwas facing difficulties.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.83,0:06:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The 55 days of continuous blitzkrieg\N thoroughly drained the Japanese army
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.96,0:06:19.54,Default,,0,0,0,,since their landing on the Malay Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.88,0:06:24.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, their ammunition needs were only 1/3 fulfilled.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.07,0:06:31.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, with the acute shortage of landing craft{/boats}, \Neven the Strait of Johor, of only 1km in width
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.53,0:06:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,could not be rowed across \Nby the troops of 5th and 18th regiments
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.93,0:06:39.67,Default,,0,0,0,,in less than 7 to 10 hours in total, \Ndespite their best effort.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.40,0:06:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,On Singapore Island,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.83,0:06:46.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy troops estimation is 70,000. \NHaving quite possibly, over 500 artillery pieces.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.11,0:06:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Even a single day allows the enemy to consolidate defenses, lowering the odds for our success. {hard fighting; hard struggle; fighting against heavy odds}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.98,0:06:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,In regard to our situation, \NI believe we should go for the shock effect,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.72,0:07:02.34,Default,,0,0,0,,so as to minimize the casualties on our side during landing.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.23,0:07:13.14,Default,,0,0,0,,No, after getting this far, \Njust crossing the strait brazenly would do. {fairly; squarely; un reservedly; brazenly}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.14,0:07:17.71,Default,,0,0,0,,As soon as we control the fresh water source from Bukit Timah Heights, they will surrender {high ground; plateau; heights}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.71,0:07:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and if they refuse, \Na deluge of artillery fire will make them. {sorry but I genuinely see 0 strategic/tactical/reason value in this plan, it makes no sense at all, especially compared to that general's proposition}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.52,0:07:25.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Any landing operation is likely \Nto cost us 1/5 of our own forces anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.65,0:07:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Northeastern coast is the fortified area, \Nlanding there will be deadly.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.67,0:07:32.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, with all our forces \Nconverging in this very part, {investment; commitment (of funds, personnel, etc.); injection; infusion}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.63,0:07:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,the sub-objective \Nof securing Bukit Timah Heights is at reach.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.68,0:07:39.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, I also don't think we have any other options.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.29,0:07:42.51,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy also knows it is a one-way trip \Nfor the landing party, {lit: there is no way out; means to escape; escape route anymore - I think he means that you can't turn back during a landing}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.51,0:07:45.13,Default,,0,0,0,,so they'll launch all their forces at stopping it. {to check; to hold back; to keep at bay; to stop; to prevent; to stem; to curb; to halt}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.13,0:07:51.62,Default,,0,0,0,,All the way from the north of Malay Peninsula - Singora, \NPattani, and Kota Bharu, we made it here to Johor Bahru{/came straight to}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.38,0:07:54.80,Default,,0,0,0,,before their most pessimistic previsions. {I think he means "we literally rushed straight to here"}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.26,0:07:58.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, the enemy still had time \Nto thoroughly prepare a counter move. {lit is "in this time, the enemy has been waiting motionlessly/gazedly/patiently/firmly - either he means the british were sitting doing nothing or that they were prepared to defent and didn't come out because were waiting for japanese to come to their prepared defenses}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.76,0:08:03.56,Default,,0,0,0,,It is now more than ever capital \Nto gather and face them all. {unsure, maybe he means "we will face their concentrated forces"}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.23,0:08:09.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Once the attack is on, \Nnone can afford to lose focus, even for a short moment. {lit: to relax (attention, efforts, etc.); to let down (one's guard); to relieve (tension) your hand}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.62,0:08:11.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The Commander-in-Chief of the British Far East
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.99,0:08:17.16,Default,,0,0,0,,still advocated defending Singapore Island \Nwith all available resources for 3 more months at least.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.16,0:08:21.04,Default,,0,0,0,,If we hold out for 3 more months, \Nwe'll buy enough time for aid to arrive{ from the homeland}.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.04,0:08:25.13,Default,,0,0,0,,If we manage to stalemate the Japanese, \Nit will be possible to counterattack.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.13,0:08:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly. But that would require us \Nto remember one thing -
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.38,0:08:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,No stirring up the soldiers \Nor the common citizens if possible. {disturbance; unrest; agitation; excitement; commotion; turmoil; discomposure; feeling shaken}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.98,0:08:35.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Are we supposed to simply bear with it? {to bear; to stand; to endure; to put up with}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.14,0:08:37.80,Default,,0,0,0,,It indeed seems impossible \Nto dodge the battle.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.80,0:08:41.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Our strategy should be defense in depth{, to then counterattack and drive the enemy back into the sea}. {lit: thorough; exhaustive; complete to charm; to attract; to fascinate; to entice​ the enemy then drive them back into the sea - no clue what he means, I'd assume "let little landing parties land then squash them" but that's be actually good strategy and not something the bri*ish would use; also they never did anything of the kind, they ended up expecting many invasions throughout the island, never fully committing to repulsing a single real one; I also hate how liberal this line, but I don't see a way to be more precise without exceeding 30 CPS}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.56,0:08:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So a coastline protection strategy?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.66,0:08:45.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Most naturally.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.31,0:08:48.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, some spark of combativeness \Nfrom you, Commander. {lit: in a positive; assertive; active; proactive; aggressive way, go into battle/show up in the war - again, I hate how liberal this line came out, if not for CPS}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.25,0:08:53.01,Default,,0,0,0,,First, we foil the enemy's attempts at landing, \Nthen we hit them back across the strait right away. {lit: at the water's edge, fight the enemy thoroughly, then immediately cross to the peninsula and strategy of close attack}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.36,0:08:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we only ensure that the island itself is defended. {to the last; persistency; thoroughness​}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.53,0:08:59.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese will do their utmost \Nto capture this point.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.20,0:09:03.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, this is a heavily fortified area. \NThe Japanese would surely enough know that much.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.79,0:09:06.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It'd drive them \Nto more vulnerable spots! {no clue what he means, HA had it "So, in other words, this is the most dangerous place." and I hear "conversely; on the contrary, here is ..." but it doesn't make sense, if he just said it's the most fortified area, it can't be the more dangerous right? I assumed "on the contrary" here to mean the only sensible thing - "we must do the opposite and bolster all the other spots"}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.37,0:09:11.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The northwestern bank is a dense mangrove jungle, \Nisn't that so, governor-general? {close thicket; dense forest; jungle} {"The British erroneously considered the jungle terrain impassable, leading to a swift Japanese advance as Allied defences were quickly outflanked."}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.50,0:09:14.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed, it's a marshland, \Nmost unwelcoming to man. {really; absolutely; truly; actually; very; quite unpleasant; disagreeable; displeasing; uncomfortable; unhappy}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.92,0:09:17.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Advancing in wetlands is extremely taxing.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.04,0:09:20.26,Default,,0,0,0,,So even the Japanese would know better \Nthan just doing this.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.26,0:09:21.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander, do you really think so? {/but it's/such a thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.71,0:09:24.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army had been straightforward \Non its way here. {lit: came to singapore in a straight line}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.64,0:09:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,attacking the forts is their most obvious choice! {lit: they'll probably attack the island fortress all at once}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.59,0:09:34.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, we'd better start \Nfortifying each and every position. {all over; everywhere; in every nook and cranny​}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.11,0:09:37.45,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no way we turn every golf course \Ninto a machine gun post. {actually he asks "you think we should build a ... on this golf course" since the 8th division commander said "all over the island" but it'd be strange of percival now to refer to just this one golf corse, that'd be out of the blue}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.45,0:09:41.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Without the city planning board's permission, \Nerecting buildings is ruled out. {lit: if we don't consult committee; commission; board; panel; committee meeting, we can't do institution; establishment; facility remodeling; remodelling; reconstruction; conversion; alteration; renovation; modification; reshuffling (e.g. a cabinet); reorganization; restructuring - again, line is liberal but at least CPS-acceptable}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.20,0:09:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,But sir, aren't we under wartime regime? {/aren't we at war?}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.08,0:09:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't want the population upset, \Nthe laborers are giving us enough problems as it is. {lit: in addition, the workers problem is severe/serious - it's not exactly the labor shortage so I think he means "local deckhands are complaining about the inconveniences of the wartime"}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.04,0:09:51.85,Default,,0,0,0,,There was no labor shortage of any sort.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.42,0:09:54.30,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the wages had to be raised.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.30,0:09:59.34,Default,,0,0,0,,The salaries far exceeded \Nthe range that the British Army Department had settled on. {this is literal and idk what he means}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.34,0:10:02.33,Default,,0,0,0,,The colonial administration's finances were strained. {lit: financially, it was becoming extremely difficult/painful}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.82,0:10:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Does that, then, mean we will sit on our hands, \Nbeing sitting ducks for the Japanese?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.28,0:10:20.79,Default,,0,0,0,,The commander of the Far Eastern British Army
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.79,0:10:24.22,Default,,0,0,0,,ordered the defenders of Singapore to be as frugal as possible {/to the best of their ability, to show thrift; economy; frugality with artillery shells}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.22,0:10:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,so as to have enough artillery shells \Nfor a 3 month siege. {/in order to hold out for 3 more months}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.18,0:10:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, the British anti-aircraft batteries were only firing \Na token amount of rounds, with little to no effect. {lit: were firing as they remembered - no clue who remembered what, maybe "they remembered the order" or something}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.98,0:11:02.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Not just that, Tengah, Sembawang, and Kallang - \Nthe only three airfields the British had
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.86,0:11:06.52,Default,,0,0,0,,were thoroughly ravaged by the Japanese bombers.{/bombed}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.20,0:12:28.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Brand new Hurricane fighters, a recent arrival \Nfrom the British mainland never managed to get airborne.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.45,0:12:31.58,Default,,0,0,0,,They were blown apart \Nright where they stood, in cold blood.{/on the ground, pitiful; tragic; horrible; miserable/cruel; merciless; atrocious; ruthless; cold-blooded as it is, they were crushed}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.34,0:12:42.94,Default,,0,0,0,,What? Drop the shell saving policy? {/stop being thrift; economy; frugality with shells}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.94,0:12:47.55,Default,,0,0,0,,No way. Intense bombardment \Nwould win us nothing but more of civilian unrest.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.81,0:12:59.82,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese were in working order \Nto commence the attack on Singapore. {/well-ordered; in good order; well-featured; well-regulated to attack ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.38,0:13:04.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant-General Yamashita set up his headquarters \Nat the Johor Bahru Royal Palace,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.46,0:13:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,in the immediate vicinity of the Strait of Johor.{/overlooking from the close distance}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.97,0:13:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,He was hoping for the upcoming \Nlanding at Singapore to be a success.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.77,0:15:42.41,Default,,0,0,0,,The 5th Division landed successfully. \NThe 18th Division landed successfully.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.73,0:15:43.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Good.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.89,0:17:47.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bukit Timah Heights were an essential stepping stone \Nin the capture of Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.10,0:17:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,This key location was where the British troops \Nshowed determined resistance for the first time.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.48,0:17:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,For the Japanese as well, \Nthe Bukit Timah Heights were the place
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.78,0:17:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,where their advance, \Nunstoppable up until now, was finally halted.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.08,0:18:06.06,Default,,0,0,0,,On the night of February 9th,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.06,0:18:10.33,Default,,0,0,0,,the Planning Staff{lit: Operation staff officer; military staff} visited the headquarters \Nof the 18th Division Command.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.00,0:18:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The overall theater commander had expressed the necessity \Nof occupying the Bukit Timah Heights by February 11th. {lit: said he wants you to ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.59,0:18:21.79,Default,,0,0,0,,As for the enemy's capitulation, \Nthe military headquarters are offering negotiation. {to come to an agreement (in bargaining, etc.); to strike a bargain}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:21.79,0:18:23.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? They want it in just 2 days?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.94,0:18:24.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.06,0:18:29.63,Default,,0,0,0,,But here, we're running short of bullets. \NAnd of shells as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.63,0:18:31.90,Default,,0,0,0,,I know the task appears taxing.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.90,0:18:36.30,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the theater commander hopes \Nto thus prevent the enemy from catching breath -
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.30,0:18:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,by seizing the Bukit Timah Heights.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.94,0:18:40.57,Default,,0,0,0,,If need be, even without bullets, with bayonet charge.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.64,0:18:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Having discussed it with the 18th division, \Nthe Planning Staff
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.08,0:18:49.12,Default,,0,0,0,,headed immediately to see the 5th division commander.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.12,0:18:54.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, the 18th Division Commander already pledged \Nto attack the Bukit Timah Heights.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.38,0:18:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, there's nothing 18th division can do that we can't.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.32,0:19:09.82,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 11th, the leaflets calling for surrender \Nwere dropped on the British positions.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.60,0:19:14.32,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the response from the British side never came.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.32,0:19:17.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bukit Timah Heights were not yet ready to capitulate.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.31,0:19:20.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll defend them. That is our only call here.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.92,0:19:55.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, it was reported that the \NImperial Guards Division launched an attack
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.25,0:19:57.58,Default,,0,0,0,,from the eastern side of the Bukit Timah Heights.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.58,0:19:58.44,Default,,0,0,0,,They started? {lit is "came?" but idk what it means}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.32,0:20:00.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.07,0:20:07.66,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 12th, at last, the Bukit Timah Heights \Nwere occupied by Japanese troops,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.66,0:20:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Making the fall of Singapore a mere matter of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.71,0:20:16.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The British command came to grips \Nwith the inevitable invasion of the city. {lit: expected/anticipated the japanese invasion; incursion; raid; aggression; intrusion; trespass; penetration; hacking}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.59,0:20:22.17,Default,,0,0,0,,To keep their facilities and equipment in Singapore \Nfrom falling into the Japanese hands, the high command {lit: the property; fortune; assets of singapore, such as building equipment; facilities; installation; accommodations; conveniences; arrangements - no clue what he means, was "public property" in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.17,0:20:25.30,Default,,0,0,0,,ordered the destruction of anything deemed of potential use.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.66,0:20:56.17,Default,,0,0,0,,I think this was their last stand. {no clue what's this about}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.67,0:21:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,On the morning of the 15th, the Chief of Staff{honestly, I have no clue what to make of those military titles anymore} \Nreported the situation to Lieutenant-General Yamashita.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.75,0:21:13.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Our side only has an average \Nof 100 shells remaining per machine gun.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.03,0:21:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Exhaustion is also taking a toll on soldiers.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.13,0:21:18.46,Default,,0,0,0,,how about we suspend the attack for a moment? {/a moment}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.46,0:21:20.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The resupply of rations is also required. {/we need a supply of food}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.03,0:21:23.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Well-rested, an army is better coordinated. {lit: after we rest, we to invade; to attack; to breach; to penetrate all at once}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.72,0:21:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It may be taxing for us. But do you think the enemy \Nis having it any easier? It's just as grueling for them.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.09,0:21:34.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Only attack. An attack here and now is the way to victory! {I feel that I'm overusing "attack" here but alas, the english doesn't have such a variety of words for it, might replace with "assault/advance"}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.50,0:21:38.50,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the battle dragged on.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.00,0:21:42.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And it only became even more grueling \Nwith a fierce British counter-attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.26,0:21:46.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it something important? {/something's the matter?}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.48,0:21:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah... No...
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.60,0:21:52.43,Default,,0,0,0,,How'd it go?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.67,0:21:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But if nothing is done\N, our side's death toll will skyrocket. {is this word appropriate here, in pre-space era? - Perevodildo}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.12,0:22:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We need to hurry and think of countermeasures.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.73,0:22:12.08,Default,,0,0,0,,What? They did it?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.04,0:22:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,At last, the Japanese army had received \Nthe British response, conceding to the capitulation offer.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.42,0:22:25.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant-General Yamashita decided to negotiate \Nwith the British in the automobile factory building,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.61,0:22:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,near the infamous Bukit Timah Heights.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.01,0:22:37.27,Default,,0,0,0,,The British army commander presented \Nvarious conditions for their surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.70,0:22:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,However, Lieutenant-General Yamashita \Nkept insisting on unconditional surrender until the very end.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.70,0:22:50.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you surrender or not?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.70,0:22:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We need "Yes" or "No"!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.03,0:22:53.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Answer just that. {/that's the only thing we want to know}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.63,0:22:55.53,Default,,0,0,0,,We've no time to waste.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.53,0:22:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.38,0:23:05.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Singapore has fallen.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.76,0:23:14.14,Default,,0,0,0,,By that time, the Japanese troops were running so low \Non shells, they had no more than 3 per machine gun. {lit is "infantry support gun" but w/e}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.60,0:23:19.29,Default,,0,0,0,,What it means to be a commander?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.10,0:23:25.90,Default,,0,0,0,,It means always being in full control of the battle, \Nit means putting yourself on the forefront, {lit is "own the battle/make fight yours" but idk what it means}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.90,0:23:28.19,Default,,0,0,0,,setting the bar for your subordinates' actions,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.19,0:23:31.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and ultimately, be there personally, \Nspearheading your men towards victory. {lit: go ahead personally, leading them to victory in the vanguard so that there is existence/presence}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.74,0:23:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,A commander, unable to abandon \Npaperwork for war, {/administrative office work}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.70,0:23:39.41,Default,,0,0,0,,leaving subordinates only the dirty bulk of the work - {/only ... are fighting}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.83,0:23:42.43,Default,,0,0,0,,is meaningless during wartime.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.83,0:23:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What the struggle for Singapore taught us is,{/battle of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.35,0:23:50.47,Default,,0,0,0,,of both opposing commanders who conducted it - \Nthe Japanese and the British one -
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.47,0:23:54.54,Default,,0,0,0,,they were, as it turns out, \Nthe embodiment of those two extremes.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.65,0:24:13.82,Default,,0,0,0,,In the wake of the Malay Peninsula invasion, \Nthe Japanese army commenced Hong Kong's.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.41,0:24:19.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Desperately, the British tried their best to hold on \Nto their fortifications on Gin Drinkers Line.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.91,0:24:23.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Until the very end, they were hoping \Nfor reinforcements, which never materialized.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.83,0:24:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army kept harassing them, \Nwave after wave. {to advance on; to close in; to march on; to descend on (the enemy); to move towards; to surge forward (crowd, wave of nostalgia, wave, etc.); to rush for (the door); to inundate; to overwhelm; to push aside like surging waves; raging billows}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.29,0:24:32.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The next decision: how should a commander \Nconduct himself on the battlefield? {the question of the way something ought to be}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.72,0:24:37.67,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 6 \NThe Fall of Hong Kong {香港攻略 - he actually says "big capture" and here it's just "capture" but w/e}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.05,0:24:35.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We present to you: \NThe Fall of Hong Kong.
